  footnotes: []
english:
  title: To My Paternal Uncle
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The west wind enters the courtyard trees on this autumn night—
    I turn my head to think of my parents: what can I do?
    The water shield of the southern river rises to the feast,
    While autumn colors of the Zhenjiang waters fill the fisherman's robe.
    Brothers without discord find joy enough in kinship,
    And fathers and elders have many pleasures in their gatherings.
    Only this troubles me—the sorrow of distant wandering:
    Dust dims my eyes, and my voice has grown strange.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhenjiang (鎭江) is a historical place in China known for its autumn scenery, used here to evoke the speaker's longing for home and loved ones.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'fisherman's robe' (蓑) is a traditional garment, but here represents the simple life of those who remain at home while the speaker travels abroad.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem subtly contrasts the warmth of family gatherings at home with the speaker's isolation and alienation in distant lands, where even his voice has become unrecognizable.
